Despite its rapid growth, Chega's political ideology has been a source of controversy. The party has been accused of promoting xenophobic and anti-democratic ideas, and its leader, André Ventura, has faced criticism for making inflammatory statements targeting minority groups. However, the party's supporters argue that it is simply giving voice to the concerns of ordinary Portuguese citizens who feel that their interests have been neglected by the traditional political parties.

As the country prepares for upcoming elections, Chega is poised to play an increasingly influential role in Portuguese politics. The party's ability to capitalize on discontent and harness the power of populist messaging has allowed it to gain a significant foothold in the political landscape, and it is likely to continue to be a force to be reckoned with in the years to come.

