      <data key="d5">TAP Air Portugal is the national airline of Portugal. It is a state-owned carrier that has been at the center of controversy in recent years.

TAP Air Portugal was originally founded in 1945 and has served as the flag carrier airline of Portugal for decades. In 2020, the airline was renationalized by the Portuguese government after a period of partial privatization. This renationalization came as TAP Air Portugal was facing significant financial difficulties and required over 2 billion euros in government aid to stay afloat.

The renationalization of TAP Air Portugal has been a source of controversy, particularly around the issue of severance payments to former executives. There were reports that the airline paid out large compensation packages to some departing managers, which drew criticism from the public and government officials. This controversy highlighted the challenges facing the airline as it sought to restructure and return to profitability with the support of the Portuguese state.

Despite the recent turmoil, TAP Air Portugal continues to operate as Portugal's national airline, serving destinations across Europe, Africa, and the Americas. The carrier plays a vital role in the country's air transportation infrastructure and economy. However, the airline's reliance on government support and the ongoing debates around its management and operations suggest that TAP Air Portugal will likely continue to face scrutiny and pressure to reform in the years ahead.

In summary, TAP Air Portugal is the state-owned national airline of Portugal that has been at the center of controversy in recent years. After being renationalized in 2020 and receiving over 2 billion euros in government aid, the airline has faced criticism over severance payments to former executives. Nevertheless, TAP Air Portugal remains an important part of Portugal's transportation network and economy, even as it works to restructure and return to financial stability.</data>
