      <data key="d2">3.0</data>
      <data key="d5">André Ventura is a Portuguese politician who is the leader of the right-wing populist Chega party. He is currently running for the position of President of Portugal.

Ventura, born in 1982, first entered the political scene in 2019 when he founded the Chega party. The party is known for its nationalist and anti-immigration stance, as well as its criticism of the political establishment. Ventura himself has been described as a right-wing populist, with his rhetoric often targeting minority groups and the perceived failures of mainstream politicians.

Despite the controversial nature of his party's platform, Ventura has managed to gain a significant following in Portugal. In the 2019 legislative elections, Chega won a single seat in the Portuguese parliament, marking the first time a far-right party had representation in the country's democratic system since the end of the dictatorship in 1974.

Ventura's decision to run for the presidency is seen by many as a strategic move to further increase the visibility and influence of his party. As a presidential candidate, he will have the opportunity to reach a wider audience and potentially sway public opinion in his favor.

However, Ventura's candidacy has also faced significant opposition from various sectors of Portuguese society. Critics have accused him of promoting divisive and intolerant policies, and have raised concerns about the potential impact of his presidency on the country's democratic institutions.

Despite these challenges, Ventura remains a polarizing figure in Portuguese politics, with his supporters praising his willingness to challenge the status quo and his opponents condemning his perceived extremism. As the presidential election approaches, the outcome of Ventura's campaign will be closely watched, both within Portugal and internationally, as a potential indicator of the broader political trends shaping the country's future.</data>
